english:
  title: Epitaph for the Tomb of An Seon, Governor of Gyerim, Posthumously Titled the Cultured and Respectful Duke
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "The An clan of Soonheung has produced many high officials since Duke Munseong Hyang. Duke Munseong's great-grandson, Jeongdang Scholar Wonsang, fathered three sons, all of whom passed the civil service examination. Duke Munseong's clansman Scholar Seok withdrew from the world and did not serve—he was the father of Master Geunjae. Though his three sons all passed the examination, and Master Geunjae's son and the current Miljeok Duke's three sons also passed, the accomplishments surpassed even those of Duke Munseong's line. Since the Yuan established the civil service system, among our Eastern people, only the Soonheung An clan and our Hansam Yi clan have had fathers and sons, or brothers in successive generations, pass the examination together. Master Gajeong studied under Master Geunjae and wrote the inscription for his tomb. When I took the provincial examination, the Master served as chief examiner. Though I am aged and infirm, I cannot refuse; how could I dare decline to compose this epitaph? \n\nThe Master possessed an open and forthright nature, loved reading the histories of the Han, and in handling affairs strove always to follow the great principles, never hesitating or looking about uncertainly. Though he drank little, he never refused wine, and would stop once drunk. In his writing, he abandoned ornament for substance, seeking only clarity. \n\nEmperor Hyungryeong recognized his virtue and resolved to employ him greatly, appointing him Secret Counselor and Expositor, concurrent Inspector and Supervisor of the Selection Bureau. He rose to Vice-Minister. In the year of Eulmi, as Vice-Minister conducting the examination, he selected thirty-three men including An Eulgi, and was appointed Jeongdang Scholar. The Master said he had found a ruler who knew him, and spoke freely without restraint. But after some time, the Emperor found him ignorant of practical affairs. Seeking to retire because his mother had grown old, the Master became Governor of Gyerim. When the government was reorganized in the year Byungshin, before he could be recalled, the Master returned to his village to serve his parents. When illness struck, he sighed: \"My mother remains well, yet my younger brother has passed, and my elder brother too. And now I... what can be done?\" Again he said: \"It is Heaven's will. What can one do?\" Soon after, he indeed departed this life. Alas, how sorrowful! How sorrowful!\n\nMaster Geunjae's son, the current Vice-Minister and Prime Minister Jongyeon, is my classmate from our examination year. He came with his brother-in-law, Vice-Minister and Prime Minister Jeong Yangbaek, and spoke thus: \"When the Cultured Duke was but nineteen, he passed the Gyeongsin examination for Jinsa. Minister Heo was his examiner. That same year he also passed the Sujaewa. Scholars Yi Igjae and Park Seokjae were the examiners. The Cultured Duke possessed inborn excellence, and our father taught him with great strictness. All marveled at his natural gifts, and valued especially that he had such worthy father and elder brother. He held many offices: District Magistrate of Gwangju, Provisional Director of Classical Studies, Censor of the Archives, Spring-Autumn Compiler, Court Artist, Gentleman of the Gate, Censorate Investigator, Military Register Assistant, Left Remonstrator, Right Counselor, Grand Ritual Official, Censorate Director, Master of Ceremonies, Grand Coordinator, Director of the Guard, Censorate Censor, Right Vice-Counselor concurrent Censor, and finally Minister of Justice. In the Academy, he rose from Expositor to Grand Expositor. He passed the Chinese Jinsa examination in the year Eulyou, was sent as envoy in Gapsin to the Yang-Gwang Road, and in Eulyou to the Gyaojo Road. On the fourth day of the ninth lunar month of Jeong-you, he passed away in Soonheung Prefecture, where he was buried. He lived fifty-six years. Now twenty-two years have passed without an inscription for his tomb. Alas, how sorrowful that the Cultured Duke left no heir! His wife, Lady Choe, had no children, leaving her without means to sustain herself through widowhood. We have been occupied with our duties and unable to devote ourselves fully to this matter, and so it has been delayed until now. Alas, how much more sorrowful!\"\n\nI said: \"Do not fear that the Master's name will not be transmitted. His examination record is preserved, his name appears on tablets, his fame spreads like wild geese returning to the pagoda, scattered across the Middle Kingdom. When people see this, who will not say, 'The An brothers of Goryeo together passed the examination'? And through their admiration spreading beyond the Eastern Sea, even were we to leave the Master's tomb unmarked, it would suffice. Moreover, his deeds are recorded in the National History. When the Records of Emperor Hyungryeong are compiled, the Master's biography will illuminate the historical records. His transmission into posterity is assured. Yet I alone grieve that he left no heir.\n\nNevertheless, among the worthy men and virtuous ones of this age—such as Yi the Attendant of the South Village, Jeong the Secret Counselor of Wugyeok, Min the Chancellor of Geuban—whose virtue and learning have become the model of the time, I have heard not even a hair's breadth of fault against them. Yet they too left no heirs. Truly, Heaven's designs are not fixed.\n\nWhen the Master supervised the Selection Bureau, I once held the brush behind him. One night he was summoned, and there was an appointment to make. Shortly after, the Emperor asked, 'What day is this?' He ordered the calendar brought and consulted it: 'It is the day of the Mad Ghost. Let us wait.' The Master, who had always despised such astrological restrictions, knelt and remonstrated: 'A Son of Heaven follows Heaven's seasons; he is not bound by such things. If the Emperor wishes to proceed, then proceed. What harm is the day of the Mad Ghost?' The Emperor's countenance changed.\n\nWhen the Master first passed the examination, he was appointed to the Yuan court as Registrar of Liaoyang and concurrent Keeper of the Archives. He said: 'Having received this appointment, to fail in my duty would be disrespectful. Moreover, the registrar merely preserves documents—what other tasks are there? I shall go to the province.' Upon arriving, the provincial officials valued his talent and treated him with courtesy. But the Master said: 'I have now fulfilled my duty. My mother is aged; to fail to return and serve her would be unfilial.' And so he resigned and returned.\n\nWhen I was in the capital, Inspector Han Jungbo told me that an official in the Ministry of Personnel, knowing the Master, had recommended him for appointment as Editor in the Academy of Worthies and the National History Institute. Yet the provincial ministers never submitted the recommendation. Though I, unworthy as I am, have inherited my ancestor's place in the Academy, the Master never received such honor. Truly, it is fate! Truly, it is fate!\n\nThe Master once said: 'Having no son, my disciples are my sons.' Among his disciples, Yi Bolin became Jeongdang Scholar; Yeom Gukbo, Yi In, and Yu Hyeonbo all became Secret Counselors and great officials. Many others rose to prominence and fame. Jeong Seuppin of Chokgye rejected Buddhism to embrace our Way. Yi Wonyeong of Gwangju fled to the wilderness to escape his enemies. The abundance of worthy men he produced was praised throughout the age.\n\nThe Master's name was Bo, his courtesy name Weonji. His grandfather and great-grandfather both served as magistrates of their prefecture. His maternal grandfather was the Inspecting General of Military Equipment.\n\nThus I inscribe:\n\nOh, the Master!\nLearning perfected,\nStrategies offered to the throne,\nHis voice echoing forth.\nServing our former king,\nCircling through the court halls,\nSpreading culture wide,\nOpening the doors to talent—\nThis was the highest glory\nOf the scholar-official.\n\nTo fail to nourish an aging mother—\nHow could the heart rest easy?\nThrough loyalty and filial piety, rising to honor,\nThe radiance of the superior man.\nSome fall short of this:\nOne must be foolish or mad.\nNow his heart is revealed,\nA regret in Moon-star City.\nThe mother lived and thrived,\nYet illness struck him down.\nClouds scattered into distance,\nAnd sorrow flowed on endlessly.\n\nVirtuous yet without a son—\nWhat mystery is this, O Heaven?\nAh, sorrowful Master!\nThe trees grow thick upon your grave,\nA thousand years hence,\nOnly your name remains.\nYet a name that shines so bright\nDoes not die with death.\nAs the Bamboo Stream has its source,\nSo flows its current long."
